  "success": true,
  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async CLI (fetch → filter → dedupe → notify), not a web/React app — there's no frontend here, so I've adapted \"N+1 queries\" and \"re-renders\" to their real analogs: per-row SQLite round-trips and per-item redundant computation. With **132 configured sources** (`sources.yaml`), several of which paginate to thousands of listings (Amazon/Microsoft/Google/Apple), these hot loops matter.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (store.py:55–74)\n\nEvery job triggers its own `SELECT`, then its own `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, in a Python `for` loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nWith potentially several thousand jobs per run across 132 sources, that's thousands of individual round-trips to SQLite (each with statement-prepare overhead) instead of a handful of set-based operations.\n\n**Fix** — load all existing hashes once, diff in memory, then batch-write:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ...)\",\n                     [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, ... WHERE key=:key\",\n                     [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                     [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(1) query + 3 batched `executemany` calls.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (filters.py:22,26)\n\n`filter_jobs()` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside that per-job call** — recompiling the identical keyword patterns from scratch for every single fetched listing:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\n**Fix** — compile once in `filter_jobs`, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re, ...)]\n```\n\nand change `match()` to just iterate the pre-compiled lists. Cheap per-call, but it's O(sources × jobs) `re.compile` invocations today for no reason.\n\n### 3. Redundant hashing — `Job.content_hash` computed twice per changed row\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` (sha256 over 4 fields), not cached. In the current `diff()`, it's computed once for the `!=` comparison and again inside `to_row()` when `_update`/`_insert` runs. Once you batch per fix #1, precompute `to_row()` a single time per job and reuse both the hash and the row dict, rather than calling the property multiple times.\n\n### 4. Missing index — `added_since()` sorts a growing table on an unindexed column (store.py:127–135, idx at line 27)\n\nThe only index is `idx_jobs_company`. `added_since()` (used by `agent.py db-new`, run every scan) filters and orders by `first_seen`, which has no index — this becomes a full table scan + sort as `jobs.db` grows across scheduled 12h runs indefinitely (nothing prunes old rows).\n\n**Fix**: `CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);`\n\n### 5. Caching opportunity — full re-fetch of every board on every 12h cron tick (fetchers.py)\n\nEvery source is fetched in full from page 1 every run (e.g. `fetch_amazon`/`fetch_microsoft` up to 40 pages, `fetch_google` up to 20), even though `Store.diff` shows the vast majority of postings are unchanged run-to-run. None of the fetchers use conditional HTTP (`If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`) or any local response cache. Since the whole pipeline runs unattended every 12 hours (per the scheduled-run commit), this is pure repeated network + parse cost with no payoff.\n\nPractical options, roughly in order of effort:\n- For ATS APIs that echo `ETag`/`Last-Modified` on their JSON responses (worth checking per-platform), thread `if-none-match` through `_request` and short-circuit on 304.\n- Cheaper: persist the previous run's raw page-1 response hash per source in `meta`, and skip paginating further only if page 1 is byte-identical to last run's page 1 for boards sorted newest-first (Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Google, Apple all sort `newest`/`recent`) — you can stop as soon as you hit a job whose `key` is already in the DB with an unchanged hash, instead of always walking to `max_pages`.\n\n### 6. Memory leaks / resource handling\n\nNo leaks found — this is a short-lived process per invocation, not a server. `httpx.AsyncClient` lifecycle in `fetch_all` (fetchers.py:1127–1148) is correctly scoped with `try/finally` + `aclose()`, and `Store` is used as a context manager everywhere it matters. Nothing accumulates across calls within a single run.\n\n### 7. \"Re-renders\" — not applicable\n\nNo React/frontend exists in this repo (it's CLI + SQLite + `templates/cv-template.html` rendered once to PDF via headless Chrome in `agent.py:pdf_render`). That path already runs once per document generation with no re-render loop to worry about.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order**: #1 (N+1 diff) and #5 (redundant full re-fetch every 12h) are the two that actually cost real wall-clock/network time at your current scale (132 sources); #2–#4 are cheap, low-risk cleanups. Want me to implement #1 and #2 now?\n",
